<h3>Make your text messages shorter</h3>
<p>You should keep text messages as short as possible. But make sure you include all the information the patient needs to know.</p>
<p>The <a href="https://service-manual.nhs.uk/content/how-we-write">How we write section of our content guide</a> can help you to write messages that are clear and concise.</p>
<h4>Use fewer fragments</h4>
<p>Text messages are split into chunks called fragments.</p>
<ul>
  <li>160 characters is 1 fragment.</li>
  <li>306 characters is 2 fragments.</li>
  <li>459 characters is 3 fragments.</li>
  <li>Each additional 153 characters is another fragment.</li>
</ul>  
<p>Each fragment costs about 2 pence.</p>  
<p>If you go 1 character over a fragment limit, you are charged for another fragment. For example:</p>  
<ul>
  <li>306 characters will be 2 fragments and cost about 4 pence</li>
  <li>307 characters will be 3 fragments and cost about 6 pence</li>
</ul>
<p>Check how many fragments your templates use. Remove any words that are not needed, for example COVID-19 guidance.</p>
<h4>Other ways to shorten text messages</h4>
<p>You can also reduce the length of your text messages by:</p>
<ul>
  <li>only using spaces and line breaks where you need to (spaces are 1 character and line breaks are 2 characters)</li>
  <li>using well-known acronyms, for example "A&E", rather than "accident and emergency"</li>
  <li>only using signs and symbols, like brackets and quote marks, if the message would be hard to understand without them</li>
  <li>writing messages directly into your messaging software, rather than copying and pasting from Word (this can add hidden characters)</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="https://www.notifications.service.gov.uk/pricing/text-messages#symbols">Find out how signs, symbols and accented characters can increase text message fragments</a>.</p>
<h4>Make sure everyone can understand your text messages</h4>
<p>Reducing the length of your text messages is important. But it is more important that all patients can understand your messages.</p>
<p> You should:</p>  
<ul>
  <li>avoid using acronyms not everyone will be familiar with, for example "OTC" for "over the counter"</li>
  <li>avoid using abbreviations, for example "Mon" for "Monday", "Feb" for "February" or "appt" for "appointment"</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="/content/messaging-patients/send-accessible-messages">Find out more about sending accessible and inclusive messages</a>.</p>
